INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8173cb14-2d28-4d43-b885-0526f8db22d9',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$esbuild Code Splitting — Manual Chunks, Dynamic Imports, and Route-Based Splitting$escape$,
  $escape$esbuild's code splitting requires two things: `format: 'esm'` and `splitting: true`. CJS output silently ignores the flag — ESM is non-negotiable. You'll also need `outdir` instead of `outfile`.

Splitting works two ways. Dynamic imports are the primary driver — any `import('...')` call causes esbuild to split the target into its own chunk, respecting the full dependency graph. Modules imported by multiple chunks are hoisted into shared chunks automatically, named by content hash unless you override with `chunkNames`.

Multiple entry points trigger manual chunking: pass an object to `entryPoints` with logical names as keys. Shared code across entries lands in auto-generated chunks — this is route-based splitting without a framework. Tree-shaking still runs per-chunk, so lazy-loaded routes won't carry dead imports from your main bundle.

One gotcha: circular ESM imports across chunk boundaries can cause runtime errors that don't surface at build time. Set `metafile: true` and inspect `outputs[entry].imports` to map chunk relationships before shipping to production.$escape$,
  $escape$// build.mjs
import { build } from 'esbuild';

await build({
  entryPoints: {
    app: 'src/app.ts',
    settings: 'src/settings.ts',
  },
  bundle: true,
  splitting: true,              // requires format: 'esm'
  format: 'esm',
  chunkNames: 'chunks/[name]-[hash]',
  outdir: 'dist',
  metafile: true,               // inspect chunk graph via outputs[].imports
  minify: true,
});$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
